<div id="review_711091465" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/711091465" />
    <a title="Christopher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12306131-christopher"><img alt="Christopher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1605156514p2/12306131.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/711091465?book_show_action=true">Sep 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher" href="/user/show/12306131-christopher">Christopher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780765347015" href="/book/show/60212.The_Knight">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer711091465" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11217721185002209717">Every Gene Wolfe novel is a f&apos;n revelation. Consistently challenging and constantly rewarding, this first of a two volume series has been described as his most &quot;accessible&quot; and it&apos;s easy to see why. It&apos;s Wolfe&apos;s turn at high fantasy. And tells the story of an American teenager who quickly finds himself (without explanation, because none is needed) transported to a fantasy world and imbued with great strength and stature and the rank of &quot;knight.&quot; <br/><br/>He quickly falls in love (lust) and goes a-questin</span>
  <span id="freeText11217721185002209717" style="display:none">Every Gene Wolfe novel is a f'n revelation. Consistently challenging and constantly rewarding, this first of a two volume series has been described as his most "accessible" and it's easy to see why. It's Wolfe's turn at high fantasy. And tells the story of an American teenager who quickly finds himself (without explanation, because none is needed) transported to a fantasy world and imbued with great strength and stature and the rank of "knight." <br /><br />He quickly falls in love (lust) and goes a-questing on behalf of his quasi-mystical love. This is Don Quixote and it's wonderful. <br /><br />Wolfe's novels are less about the destination than they are about the journey and this is one is no different. But with every encounter, he imbues Sir Able of the High Heart (because he's a knight you know) with the arrogance and ignorance that all teenage boys would act with if thrust into the "hero" role they so thoroughly crave and fear. <br /><br />Wonderful in every respect. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11217721185002209717" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


